passages.text: Share Price Performance (pg.8- 9) - The European Internet sector traded down \(3\%\) last week, underperforming both the US Internet sector (flat) and the wider Euro Stoxx 600 Tech Index (- 1%). The sector's performance was weak across sub- sectors with Classifieds and eCommerce & Others trading down \(2\%\) and \(- 4\%\) respectively, driven by RMV (- 3%), OCDO (- 6%) and HFG (- 7%), while Food Delivery traded down \(1\%\) with DHER (- 5%).

Consensus Revisions (pg.10- 11) - Looking at 1- year forward revenue consensus on a 4- week rolling basis, we saw upgrades at ATG (+18% on M&A) and AG1 (+6%). We also note downgrades at HFG (- 4%) and EVD (- 2%). With regard to EBITDA consensus on a last 4w rolling basis, we saw consensus upgrades at AG1 (+8%) and DHER (+3%) and downgrades at OCDO (- 9%) and THG (- 4%).

Multiple Developments (pg.12- 16) - Price performance and multiple trends remain diverse across sub- sectors and levels of resiliency and profitability. Share prices of low profitability/unprofitable names in our coverage universe increased \(c.69\%\) in the last 12 months and the high- profitability sub- sector increased by \(c.4\%\) . In terms of multiples development, AG1 and VEND saw a 1- year forward EV/Sales multiples re- rate (+142% and +107%), with de- ratings THG (- 54%) and HEM (- 53%). For profitable names, we are seeing the strongest re- rating in 1yr forward EV/EBITDA multiples at G24 (+38%) and RMV (+20%), with a meaningful de- rating at DEC (- 34%). With the sector trading at c.7- 19x 2026E EV/EBITDA for a 2- year CAGR of +16% in Classifieds and +10% in eCommerce & Others, we find valuation is attractive vs. Consumer, with the MSCI Consumer Discretionary index trading at 6.7x for +7% CAGR.

JPME vs. Consensus (pg.7) - Reviewing latest consensus - upside/downside in focus. Looking to 2025/2026 revenue, we would call out upside in DHER (+7%/+2%) and CTs (+6%/+5%) and looking at our FY25/26 EBITDA estimates, we are also above consensus on Auto1 (+6%/+9%) and G24 (+2%/+6%). Conversely, we are below FY25/26 EBITDA estimates on Auto Trader (- 3%/- 4%) and Rightmove (- 1%/- 2%).
Insider Transactions (pg.17). Limited transactions in CTS Eventum, Scout24 and YouGov.

Bond and Buyback Tracker (pg.18- 20). We continue to run two key trackers across our coverage: (1) pricing and details of the sector, and (2) latest updates on the buyback programmes that have not been completed.

Internet Screener - M&A, Profitability, Multiples, Balance Sheet, Momentum (pg.33- 37) - Our European Internet Screener preference is geared towards M&A upside and tipping point profitability in 2025, while we also favour earnings upside risk and strong, non- cyclical earnings momentum. Our M&A screener suggests the highest ranking for JET and Future. Our Profitability screener sees the top 3 names as JET, HelloFresh and Auto Hard the bottom is HG. For our Multiples screener (lowest multiples in the sector) the top 3 are Future, HelloFresh and Delivery Hero, while Ocado screens the weakest. We see the best balance sheet positions for Vend Marketplaces and CTS Eventum, and the bottom 3 in our rankings are Ocado, Ströer and ATG. We saw the strongest momentum in JET, ATG and Trailer and the weakest is CTS Eventum.

Our Recent Publications and Upcoming Events - Delivery Hero reported a good set of Q225 results, in our view (HERE), with revenues and H1 Group EBITDA coming ahead of consensus. While FY25 guidance was cut driven by FX effects (mostly Korea but also MENA which is pegged to the USD), trading conditions in Asia are improving and the company generated its first positive EBIT (€5m) in H1. Post the results, management hosted a reassuring conference call confirming its anticipation of Korea/Asia GMV growth returning by Q4 this year with new product rollouts and efficiency improvements. We reiterated our Overweight rating on the name (HERE), and see a buying opportunity at these levels, arguing Delivery Hero still provides a high degree of strategic value for Prosus, with the announced sell- down potentially reassessed once the Just Eat transaction closes in early October. CD Projekt reported another good set of results (HERE), with group revenues and EBIT coming in ahead of expectations. Looking ahead, management continues to ramp up investments in ongoing projects with Cyberpunk 2 now firmly in pre- production phase, the execution of which we will continue to monitor along with the timeline to release.

August 27th, 2025: Hemnet (N) - Hemnet has appointed Marcus Westerlund as Chief Sales Officer and member of the Group Management Team, effective September 1. Marcus, who joined Hemnet as Sales Director in August 2024, previously held senior sales leadership roles at Prisjakt, including Chief Sales Officer. At Hemnet, Marcus leads the advertising sales team and is responsible for strengthening customer relationships and partnerships, particularly with Sweden's real estate agents. As of September 1, the responsibility will be expanded to also include customer service.

With sector multiles having materialy de- rated, we believe it is important to consider the attractiveness of a company to a strategic/financial investor and/or the likelihood of companies disposing assets to unlock value. We highlight our view that M&A activity is likely to continue in the European Internet space going forward, especially in the Food Delivery space. Our M&A framework assesses the potential of this and we rate each company on a scale from 1 to 5, with 5 being most vulnerable to M&A opportunities. We also flag factors that may impact M&A potential, such as shareholdings and share class structure (free float).

We now see higher scope for outperformance for companies in the early stages of profitability (and likely underperformance if EBIT profitability is still not reached in 2026). To reach our final ranking within the profitability upside screen, we solely look at 2026E EBIT margin improvement versus 2025E but note that we still rank the unprofitable players for 2026E (on an EBIT basis) at the bottom. Overall, Online Food Delivery scans well given the turning point in profitability, while Online Classifieds, excluding Auto1, scan less well as their margins offer limited upside, in our view.

We screen performance across our space in the 2 trading days post the US election to highlight names that should benefit under the Trump presidency. We note that there was a high degree of volatility during this period given results for Delivery Hero, Trainline and Auto Trader that skews the perceived impact of election results. We do not see President Trump's election as key for the sector and view the impact of his election as limited. We note that his administration is expected to take a more aggressive stance on Big Tech and China, which may carry negative implications for the industry. However, expected lower corporate taxes would be supportive to US- exposed names within our coverage (notably ATG and HelloFresh).

1. BCG is the largest (and dominant) online Classifieds player in the Baltic region, with operations in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. The company is active (and mostly market leading) in all key Classifieds verticals such as real estate, cars, jobs, and general goods, facilitating transactions between individuals and businesses. We argue for high visibility of BCG's earnings growth given improved monetization of its Classifieds portfolio, with still ample room in particular to drive ARPU and customer numbers from here.
2. While the multiple is high, we see a premium to peers as justified given higher growth potential in the long term and M&A upside risk.
